{"title_page": "Alphabet Inc.", "text_new": "{{Redirect|GOOGL|the company formerly traded under the ticker symbol|Google}}\n{{short description|American holding company}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Alphabet Inc.\n| logo                = Alphabet Inc Logo 2015.svg\n| logo_alt            = The letters of \"Alphabet\" colored in red\n| image               = Googleplex HQ (cropped).jpg\n| image_size          = 260px\n| image_caption       = [[Googleplex]], home to Alphabet Inc., in [[Mountain View, California|Mountain View]], California\n| type                = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as           = {{Unbulleted list\n| Class A: {{NASDAQ|GOOGL}}\n| Class B: Unlisted\n| Class C: {{NASDAQ|GOOG}}\n| [[NASDAQ-100]] components (A & C)\n| [[S&P 100]] components (A & C)\n| [[S&P 500]] components (A & C)\n}}\n| ISIN                = US02079K3059\n| ISIN2               = US02079K1079\n| industry            = [[Conglomerate (company)|Conglomerate]]\n| founded             = {{Start date and age|2015|10|02}}\n| founders            = {{Unbulleted list\n| [[Larry Page]]\n| [[Sergey Brin]]\n}}\n| hq_location         = [[Googleplex]]\n| hq_location_city    = [[Mountain View, California]]\n| hq_location_country = [[US]]\n| area_served         = Worldwide\n| key_people          = {{Unbulleted list\n| [[Larry Page]] (co-founder)\n| [[Sergey Brin]] (co-founder)\n| [[Sundar Pichai]] (CEO)\n| [[John L. Hennessy]] (chair)\n| [[Ruth Porat]] (CFO)\n| [[Eric Schmidt]] (technical advisor)\n}}\n| products            = [[Technology]]\n| revenue             = {{Unbulleted list|class=nowrap|{{Increase}} {{US$|161.857 [[1,000,000,000|billion]]|link=yes}} (2019)|{{Increase}} {{US$|136.819 [[1,000,000,000|billion]]|link=yes}} (2018)}}\n| revenue_year        =\n| operating_income    = {{Increase}} {{US$|34.23&nbsp;billion}}\n| income_year         = 2019\n| net_income          = {{Increase}} {{BDT|34.34&nbsp;billion}}\n| net_income_year     = 2019\n| assets              = {{Increase}} {{US$|275.9&nbsp;billion}}\n| assets_year         = 2019\n| equity              = {{Increase}} {{US$|201.4&nbsp;billion}}\n| equity_year         = 2019\n| num_employees       = {{Increase}} 118,899\n| num_employees_year  = 2019\n| subsid              = {{Hlist\n| [[Calico (company)|Calico]]\n| [[CapitalG]]\n| [[DeepMind]]\n| [[Google]]\n| [[Google Fiber]]\n| [[GV (company)|GV]]\n| [[Loon (company)|Loon]]\n| [[Sidewalk Labs]]\n| [[Verily]]\n| [[Waymo]]\n| [[Wing (company)|Wing]]\n| [[X (company)|X]]\n}}\n| website             = {{URL| https://abc.xyz/}}\n| footnotes           = <ref name=\"fy2019\">{{cite web|url=https://abc.xyz/investor/static/pdf/2019Q4_alphabet_earnings_release.pdf?cache=adc3b38 |title=Alphabet Announces Fourth Quarter and Fiscal Year 2019 Results |website=abc.xyz |publisher=Alphabet Inc. |date=February 3, 2020 |accessdate=March 2, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Alphabet Inc.''' is an American multinational [[conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]] headquartered in [[Mountain View, California]]. It was created through a [[restructuring]] of [[Google]] on October 2, 2015,<ref name=\"sec\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1652044/000119312515336577/d82837d8k12b.htm |title=SEC Filing (Form 8-K) by Alphabet Inc. |publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] |date=October 2, 2015}}</ref> and became the parent company of Google and several former Google [[Subsidiary|subsidiaries]].<ref name=\"aol\">{{cite web |title=Google to be part of new holding company, 'Alphabet' |url=https://www.aol.com/article/2015/08/10/google-to-be-part-of-new-holding-company-alphabet/21220854/ |accessdate=August 11, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"gIsForGoogle\">{{cite web |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.com/2015/08/google-alphabet.html |title=G is for Google |publisher=Google Official Blog |last1=Page |first1=Larry |accessdate=August 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/google-restructures-into-alphabet-soup-of-businesses/|title=Google creates new parent company called Alphabet|date=August 10, 2015|publisher=CNET|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150917083700/https://www.cnet.com/news/google-restructures-into-alphabet-soup-of-businesses/|archive-date=September 17, 2015|url-status = live|accessdate=September 19, 2015}}</ref> The two founders of Google assumed executive roles in the new company, with [[Larry Page]] serving as CEO and [[Sergey Brin]] as president.<ref name=\"bloomberg2015\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-08-10/google-to-adopt-new-holding-structure-under-name-alphabet-|title=Google Creates New Company Called Alphabet, Restructures Stock|last1=Womack|first1=Brian|date=August 10, 2015|accessdate=August 10, 2015|agency=Bloomberg}}</ref> Alphabet is the [[List of largest technology companies by revenue|world's fourth-largest technology company]] by revenue and one of the [[List of public corporations by market capitalization|world's most valuable companies]].<ref name=\"Fortune\">{{cite news | url=http://beta.fortune.com/global500/list/filtered?sector=Technology | title=Top 50 Global Technology Companies | publisher=Fortune Global 500 | access-date=June 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170126084151/http://beta.fortune.com/global500/list/filtered?sector=Technology | archive-date=January 26, 2017 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Alphabet|url=https://www.forbes.com/companies/alphabet/|work=Forbes|accessdate=June 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe establishment of Alphabet was prompted by a desire to make the core Google business \"cleaner and more accountable\" while allowing greater autonomy to group companies that operate in businesses other than Internet services.<ref name=\"gIsForGoogle\" /><ref name=\"wire-2015-new-company\">{{cite journal|last1=Metz|first1=Cade|date=August 10, 2015|title=A New Company Called Alphabet Now Owns Google|url=https://www.wired.com/2015/08/new-company-called-alphabet-owns-google/|journal=[[Wired (website)|Wired]]|accessdate=August 13, 2015}}</ref> Page and Brin announced their resignation from their executive posts in December 2019, with the CEO role to be filled by [[Sundar Pichai]], also the CEO of Google. Page and Brin remain co-founders, employees, board members, and [[controlling interest|controlling shareholders]] of Alphabet Inc.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jilliandonfro/2019/12/03/larry-page-steps-down-as-ceo-of-google-parent-alphabet/|title=Larry Page Steps Down As CEO Of Alphabet|last=Donfro|first=Jillian|date=December 3, 2019|website=Forbes|access-date=December 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nOn August 10, 2015, [[Google|Google Inc.]] announced plans to create a new public [[holding company]], Alphabet Inc. Google CEO [[Larry Page]] made this announcement in a blog post on Google's official blog.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://money.cnn.com/2015/08/10/technology/alphabet-google/index.html|title=Meet Google Alphabet \u2013 Google's new parent company|last=Kelly|first=Heather|date=August 10, 2015|website=CNNMoney|access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> Alphabet would be created to restructure Google by moving subsidiaries from Google to Alphabet, narrowing Google's scope. The company would consist of Google as well as other businesses including [[X (company)|X Development]], [[Calico (company)|Calico]], [[Google Nest|Nest]], [[Verily]], Fiber, [[Makani (company)|Makani]], [[CapitalG]], and [[GV (company)|GV]].<ref name=\"bloomberg2015\" /><ref>{{cite journal |title=What Google, I Mean Alphabet, Looks Like Now |url=https://www.wired.com/2015/08/google-mean-alphabet-looks-like-now/ |accessdate=August 10, 2015 |date=August 10, 2015 |first=Julia |last=Greenberg |journal=[[Wired (website)|Wired]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=What is Alphabet, Google's new company? |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/what-is-alphabet-googles-new-company-2015-8 |accessdate=August 10, 2015 |work=Business Insider}}</ref> [[Sundar Pichai]], Product Chief, became the new CEO of Google, replacing [[Larry Page]], who transitioned to the role of running Alphabet, along with Google co-founder Sergey Brin.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-creates-new-company-alphabet-1439240645 |title=Google Creates Parent Company Called Alphabet in Restructuring |last=Chen |first=Angela |date=August 10, 2015 |work=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=August 10, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT_2015_Dougherty\">{{cite news |title=Google to Reorganize in Move to Keep Its Lead as an Innovator |first=Conor |last=Dougherty |date=August 10, 2015 |accessdate=August 10, 2015 |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/11/technology/google-alphabet-restructuring.html}}</ref>\n\nIn his announcement, Page described the planned holding company as follows:<ref name=\"gIsForGoogle\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |title=Google's Larry Page explains the new Alphabet |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/googles-larry-page-explains-the-new-alphabet/ |publisher=CNET |accessdate=September 19, 2015}}</ref>\n{{quote|Alphabet is mostly a collection of companies. The largest of which, of course, is Google. This newer Google is a bit slimmed down, with the companies that are pretty far afield of our main internet products contained in Alphabet instead. ... Fundamentally, we believe this allows us more management scale, as we can run things independently that aren't very related.}}\n\nPage says the motivation behind the reorganization is to make Google \"cleaner and more accountable and better\". He also said he wanted to improve \"the transparency and oversight of what we're doing\", and to allow greater control of unrelated companies.<ref name=\"gIsForGoogle\" /><ref name=\"wire-2015-new-company\" />\n\nFormer executive Eric Schmidt (now Technical Advisor) revealed in the conference in 2017 the inspiration for this structure came from Warren Buffett and his management structure of Berkshire Hathaway a decade ago.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/google-founders-modeled-alphabet-warren-buffett-berkshire-hathaway-2019-12-1028737463|title=Google's founders came up with the Alphabet model after meeting Warren Buffett {{!}} Markets Insider|last=GmbH|first=finanzen net|website=Business Insider|access-date=December 5, 2019}}</ref> Schmidt said it was he who encouraged Page and Brin to meet with Buffett in Omaha to see how Berkshire Hathaway was a holding company made of subsidiaries with strong CEOs who were trusted to run their businesses.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nBefore it became a subsidiary of Alphabet, Google Inc. was first structured as the owner of Alphabet. The roles were reversed after a placeholder subsidiary was created for the ownership of Alphabet, at which point the newly formed subsidiary was merged with Google. Google's stock was then converted to Alphabet's stock. Under the [[Delaware General Corporation Law]] (where Alphabet is incorporated), a holding company reorganization such as this can be done without a vote of shareholders, as this reorganization was.<ref name=\"SEC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1288776/000128877615000039/a20150810form8-k.htm|title=Google Inc. filing with the SEC, Form 8-K|date=August 10, 2015|publisher=[[United States Securities and Exchange Commission]]|accessdate=August 11, 2015}}</ref> The restructuring process was completed on October 2, 2015.<ref name=\"sec\" /> Alphabet retains Google Inc.'s stock price history and continues to trade under Google Inc.'s former ticker symbols \"GOOG\" and \"GOOGL\"; both classes of stock are components of major [[stock market index|stock market indices]] such as the [[S&P 500]] and [[NASDAQ-100]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/GOOGL/|title=GOOGL : Summary for Alphabet Inc.|publisher=Yahoo! Finance|access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn December 3, 2019, Page and Brin jointly announced that they would step down from their respective roles, remaining as employees and still the majority vote on the board of directors. [[Sundar Pichai]], the CEO of Google, is to assume the CEO role at Alphabet while retaining the same at Google.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/12/03/larry-page-steps-down-as-ceo-of-alphabet.html|title=Larry Page steps down as CEO of Alphabet, Sundar Pichai to take over|last=Feiner|first=Lauren|date=December 3, 2019|publisher=CNBC|access-date=December 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Structure ==\nAlphabet's largest subsidiary is Google. Its other subsidiaries include [[Calico (company)|Calico]], [[DeepMind]], [[GV (company)|GV]], [[Google Capital|CapitalG]], [[X (company)|X]], [[Google Fiber]], [[Makani (company)|Makani]], [[Sidewalk Labs]], [[Verily Life Sciences|Verily]], [[Waymo]], [[Wing (company)|Wing]] and [[Loon LLC|Loon]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719182259/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-44886803|title=Google's Loon brings internet-by-balloon to Kenya \u2013 BBC News|date=July 19, 2018|website=web.archive.org|access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/alphabet-google-company-list-2017-4|title=All the companies and divisions under Google's parent company, Alphabet|last=Hartmans|first=Avery|website=Business Insider|access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/11/21133398/google-jigsaw-waymo-nest-brin-page-alphabet|title=Alphabet has moved technology incubator Jigsaw under Google management \u2013 The Verge|date=February 11, 2020|website=The Verge|access-date=February 20, 2020}}</ref> {{as of|2017|September|1|df=US}}, their equity is held by a subsidiary known as '''XXVI Holdings, Inc.''' (referring to the Roman numeral of 26, the number of letters in the alphabet), so that they can be valued and legally separated from Google. At the same time, it was announced that Google will be reorganized as a [[limited liability company]], Google LLC.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-09-01/alphabet-wraps-up-reorganization-with-a-new-company-called-xxvi |title=Alphabet Finishes Reorganization With New XXVI Company |date=September 1, 2017 |publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|access-date=September 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/09/04/google-parent-alphabet-forms-holding-company-xxvi-to-complete-2015-corporate-reorganization/|title=Google parent Alphabet forms holding company, XXVI, to complete 2015 corporate reorganization|website=TechCrunch|access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Eric Schmidt]] said at an [[Internet Association]] event in 2015 that there may eventually be more than 26 Alphabet subsidiaries. He also said that he was currently meeting with the CEOs of the current and proposed Alphabet subsidiaries. He said, \"You'll see a lot coming.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2015/10/13/11619552/eric-schmidt-get-ready-for-a-lot-more-alphabet-companies|title=Eric Schmidt: Get Ready for 'a Lot' More Alphabet Companies|last1=Bergen|first1=Mark|date=October 13, 2015|website=Vox|publisher=Re/code|accessdate=October 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nWhile many companies or divisions formerly a part of Google became subsidiaries of Alphabet, Google remains the umbrella company for Alphabet's Internet-related businesses. These include widely used products and services long associated with Google, such as the [[Android (operating system)|Android mobile operating system]], YouTube, and [[Google Search]], which remain direct components of Google.<ref name=\"bloomberg2015\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Google's new Alphabet, from A to Z (pictures) |url=https://www.cnet.com/pictures/googles-new-alphabet-from-a-to-z/ |publisher=CNET |accessdate=August 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFormer subsidiaries include [[Nest Labs]], which was merged into Google in February 2018<ref>{{cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2018/02/nest-is-done-as-a-standalone-alphabet-company-merges-with-google/ |title=Nest is done as a standalone Alphabet company, merges with Google |first=Ron |last=Amadeo |date=February 7, 2018 |website=Ars Technica}}</ref> and [[Chronicle (company)|Chronicle]] which was merged with Google Cloud in June 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cloud.google.com/blog/topics/inside-google-cloud/the-security-moonshot-joins-google-cloud |title=Google Cloud + Chronicle: The security moonshot joins Google Cloud |first=Thomas |last=Kurian |date=June 27, 2019 |website=Inside Google Cloud}}</ref>\n\n== Corporate identity ==\nPage explained the origin of the company's name:<ref name=\":0\" />\n{{quote|We liked the name Alphabet because it means a collection of letters that represent language, one of humanity's most important innovations, and is the core of how we index with Google search! We also like that it means alpha\u2011bet ([[Alpha (finance)|Alpha]] is investment return above benchmark), which we strive for!}}\n\nIn a 2018 talk, Schmidt disclosed that the original inspiration for the name came from the location of the then Google Hamburg office's street address: {{Interlanguage link|ABC-Stra\u00dfe|de}}.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wie die Hamburger ABC-Stra\u00dfe Google pr\u00e4gte |url=https://www.abendblatt.de/hamburg/hamburg-mitte/article215905959/Wie-die-Hamburger-ABC-Strasse-Google-praegte.html |website=abendblatt.de |accessdate=November 30, 2018|date=November 29, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAlphabet has chosen the domain abc.xyz with the [[.xyz]] [[top-level domain]] (TLD), which was introduced in 2014. It does not own the domain alphabet.com, which is owned by a [[fleet management]] division of [[BMW]]. BMW has said that it is \"necessary to examine the legal trademark implications\" of the proposals. Additionally, it does not own the domain abc.com, which is the promoted domain of the [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]]-owned [[American Broadcasting Company]] (abc.com redirects to a subdomain of [[go.com]], through which most of Disney's sites are hosted).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Davidson |first1=Lauren |title=Google unveils Alphabet... but that's already trademarked by BMW |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/mediatechnologyandtelecoms/11797616/Google-unveils-Alphabet...-but-thats-already-trademarked-by-BMW.html |website=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=August 12, 2015|date=August 11, 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"tc-alphabet-bmw\">{{cite news |last1=Lardinois |first1=Frederic |title=Google Is Now Alphabet, But It Doesn't Own Alphabet.com |url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/08/10/google-is-now-alphabet-but-it-doesnt-own-alphabet-com/ |accessdate=August 11, 2015 |work=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL Inc. |date=August 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe website features an [[Easter egg (media)|Easter egg]] in the paragraph where Larry Page writes, \"Sergey and I are seriously in the business of starting new things. Alphabet will also include our [[Google X Labs|X lab]], which incubates new efforts like [[X (company)#Wing|Wing]], our [[drone delivery]] effort. We are also stoked about growing our investment arms, Ventures and Capital, as part of this new structure.\" The period after \"drone delivery effort\" is a [[hyperlink]] to \"hooli.xyz\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hooli.xyz/#inspiration |title=hooli}}</ref> a reference to the television series ''[[Silicon Valley (TV series)|Silicon Valley]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/aug/11/google-silicon-valley-spinal-tap-tech |date=August 12, 2015 |accessdate=February 28, 2016 |title=Google's hooli.xyz Easter egg proves Silicon Valley is tech's own Spinal Tap |first=David |last=Stubbs | authorlink = David Stubbs|work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\n== Revenue ==\nAs per its 2017 annual report, 86% of Alphabet's revenues came from performance advertising (through user clicks using [[Adsense]] and [[Google Ads]]) and brand advertising.<ref name=\"agm2017\">{{cite book |title=Annual report 2017 |date=March 2, 2018 |publisher=Alphabet investor relations |pages=2, 3, 5, 6 |url=https://abc.xyz/investor |accessdate=December 3, 2018}}</ref> Of these, 53% came from its international operations. This translated to a total revenue of US$110,855&nbsp;million in 2017 and a net income of US$12,662&nbsp;million.\n\nOn February 1, 2016, Alphabet Inc. surpassed [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] to become the world's most valuable publicly traded company until February 3, 2016, when Apple surged back over Alphabet to retake the position. Experts cited Apple's lack of innovation as well as increasing Chinese competition as reasons for the poor performance.<ref name=\"alphabet-most-valuable\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2016/02/01/google-passes-apple-as-most-valuable-company.html|title=Google passes Apple as most valuable company|last1=Levy|first1=Ari|website=[[CNBC]].com|publisher=[[NBCUniversal]]|accessdate=February 1, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"apple-most-valuable\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/markets/2016/02/03/apple-not-going-down-easy/79763410/|title=Apple not going down easy as it overtakes Google parent Alphabet|last1=Krantz|first1=Matt|website=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=February 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n{{as of|2019|||df=}}, Alphabet is ranked No. 15 on the [[Fortune 500]] rankings of the largest United States corporations by total revenue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/fortune500/2019/search/|title=Fortune 500|website=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]|url-status=live|access-date=November 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn January 16, 2020, Alphabet became the fourth US company to reach a $1 [[trillion]] market value<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/alphabet-becomes-fourth-u-s-company-to-ever-reach-1-trillion-market-value-11579208802|title=Alphabet Becomes Fourth U.S. Company to Reach $1 Trillion Market Value|last=Ramkumar|first=Amrith|website=The Wall Street Journal|access-date=January 19, 2020}}</ref> entering the [[List of public corporations by market capitalization|Trillion dollar companies club]] for the first time.\n\n== Investments and acquisitions ==\n\n=== Investments ===\nIn November 2017, Alphabet Inc. led a Series A round of $71&nbsp;million along with [[Andreessen Horowitz]] and [[20th Century Fox]] in music startup [[UnitedMasters]], founded by [[Steve Stoute]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/11/15/united-masters/ |title=With $70M from Alphabet, UnitedMasters replaces record labels |last=Constine |first=Josh |work=TechCrunch|access-date=December 4, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n=== Acquisitions ===\n{{Main|List of mergers and acquisitions by Alphabet}}\nAn analysis of the company's investments in 2017 suggested that it was the most active investor in that period, outdoing the capital arm of [[Intel]] and also its own best customer. Alphabet, Inc. acquired seven of its own capital-backed startups in the 2017 financial year, with [[Cisco]] second having acquired six of the company's previous investments.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/02/17/a-peek-inside-alphabets-investing-universe/ |title=A peek inside Alphabet's investing universe |work=[[Techcrunch]] |date=February 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFlatiron Health, a startup founded by two former Google employees and backed by Alphabet, Inc., announced that it was to be acquired by health conglomerate [[Hoffmann-La Roche]] for $1.8&nbsp;billion. The company provides electronic medical records and analysis to identify improved treatments for [[oncology]] patients.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/02/15/roche-buying-flatiron-health-backed-by-alphabet.html |title=Alphabet-backed Flatiron Health is being acquired by Roche |publisher=CNBC |first=Christina |last=Farr |date=February 15, 2018| access-date= March 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Lawsuit==\nAlphabet Inc. sued [[Uber]] over technology similar to Alphabet's proprietary self-driving car technology.{{when|date=February 2020}} Alphabet's [[autonomous vehicle]] technology has been under development for a decade by Alphabet's [[Waymo]] (self-driving vehicle division). The [[proprietary software|proprietary technology]] is related to 14,000 documents believed to have been downloaded and stolen by a former Waymo engineer, subsequently employed by Uber.<ref name=\"suit\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-uber-alphabet-lawsuit-idUSKBN18Q2CW|title=Uber fires self-driving car chief at center of court case|last1=Sage|first1=Alexandria|date=May 30, 2017|accessdate=May 30, 2017|agency=Reuters}}</ref><ref name=\"selfdrive\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/30/technology/uber-anthony-levandowski.html|title=Uber Fires Former Google Engineer at Heart of Self-Driving Dispute|last1=Isaac|first1=Mike|date=May 30, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=May 30, 2017|last2=Wakabayashi|first2=Daisuke}}</ref> The lawsuit was settled in February 2018, with Uber agreeing not to use the self-driving technology in dispute and also agreed to provide [[Waymo]] with an equity stake of 0.34%, equating to around $245&nbsp;million at the firm's early 2018 value.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/02/09/uber-waymo-lawsuit-settlement.html|title=Uber settles dispute with Alphabet's self driving car unit|last1=Balakrishnan|first1=Anita|date=February 9, 2018|publisher=CNBC|last2=D'Onfro|first2=Jillian|last3=Bosa|first3=Deirdre|last4=Zaveri|first4=Paayal}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* {{Portal inline|size=tiny|Internet}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Alphabet Inc.}}\n* {{official website}}\n{{Finance links\n| name = Alphabet Inc. (class A)\n| symbol = GOOGL\n| sec_cik = GOOGL\n| yahoo = GOOGL\n| google = GOOGL\n| reuters = GOOGL.O\n| bloomberg = GOOGL:US\n}}\n{{Finance links\n| name = Alphabet Inc. (class C)\n| symbol = GOOG\n| sec_cik = GOOG\n| yahoo = GOOG\n| google = GOOG\n| reuters = GOOG.O\n| bloomberg = GOOG:US\n}}\n\n{{Alphabet Inc.|state=expanded}}\n{{Google Inc.}}\n{{NASDAQ-100}}\n\n[[Category:Alphabet Inc.| ]]\n[[Category:2015 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 2015]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Mountain View, California]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Silicon Valley]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on NASDAQ]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 2015]]\n[[Category:Conglomerate companies established in 2015]]\n[[Category:Conglomerate companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Google]]\n[[Category:Holding companies established in 2015]]\n[[Category:Holding companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in the United States]]\n[[Category:Technology companies based in the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Technology companies established in 2015]]\n[[Category:Video game companies based in California]]\n[[Category:Biotechnology companies of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|GOOGL|the company formerly traded under the ticker symbol|Google}}\n{{short description|American holding company}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=February 2020}}\n{{Infobox company\n| name                = Alphabet Inc.\n| logo                = Alphabet Inc Logo 2015.svg\n| logo_alt            = The letters of \"Alphabet\" colored in red\n| image               = Googleplex HQ (cropped).jpg\n| image_size          = 260px\n| image_caption       = [[Googleplex]], home to Alphabet Inc., in [[Mountain View, California|Mountain View]], California\n| type                = [[Public company|Public]]\n| traded_as           = {{Unbulleted list\n| Class A: {{NASDAQ|GOOGL}}\n| Class B: Unlisted\n| Class C: {{NASDAQ|GOOG}}\n| [[NASDAQ-100]] components (A & C)\n| [[S&P 100]] components (A & C)\n| [[S&P 500]] components (A & C)\n}}\n| ISIN                = US02079K3059\n| ISIN2               = US02079K1079\n| industry            = [[Conglomerate (company)|Conglomerate]]\n| founded             = {{Start date and age|2015|10|02}}\n| founders            = {{Unbulleted list\n| [[Larry Page]]\n| [[Sergey Brin]]\n}}\n| hq_location         = [[Googleplex]]\n| hq_location_city    = [[Mountain View, California]]\n| hq_location_country = [[US]]\n| area_served         = Worldwide\n| key_people          = {{Unbulleted list\n| [[Larry Page]] (co-founder)\n| [[Sergey Brin]] (co-founder)\n| [[Sundar Pichai]] (CEO)\n| [[John L. Hennessy]] (chair)\n| [[Ruth Porat]] (CFO)\n| [[Eric Schmidt]] (technical advisor)\n}}\n| products            = [[Technology]]\n| revenue             = {{Unbulleted list|class=nowrap|{{Increase}} {{US$|161.857 [[1,000,000,000|billion]]|link=yes}} (2019)|{{Increase}} {{US$|136.819 [[1,000,000,000|billion]]|link=yes}} (2018)}}\n| revenue_year        =\n| operating_income    = {{Increase}} {{US$|34.23&nbsp;billion}}\n| income_year         = 2019\n| net_income          = {{Increase}} {{US$|34.34&nbsp;billion}}\n| net_income_year     = 2019\n| assets              = {{Increase}} {{US$|275.9&nbsp;billion}}\n| assets_year         = 2019\n| equity              = {{Increase}} {{US$|201.4&nbsp;billion}}\n| equity_year         = 2019\n| num_employees       = {{Increase}} 118,899\n| num_employees_year  = 2019\n| subsid              = {{Hlist\n| [[Calico (company)|Calico]]\n| [[CapitalG]]\n| [[DeepMind]]\n| [[Google]]\n| [[Google Fiber]]\n| [[GV (company)|GV]]\n| [[Loon (company)|Loon]]\n| [[Sidewalk Labs]]\n| [[Verily]]\n| [[Waymo]]\n| [[Wing (company)|Wing]]\n| [[X (company)|X]]\n}}\n| website             = {{URL| https://abc.xyz/}}\n| footnotes           = <ref name=\"fy2019\">{{cite web|url=https://abc.xyz/investor/static/pdf/2019Q4_alphabet_earnings_release.pdf?cache=adc3b38 |title=Alphabet Announces Fourth Quarter and Fiscal Year 2019 Results |website=abc.xyz |publisher=Alphabet Inc. |date=February 3, 2020 |accessdate=March 2, 2020}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''Alphabet Inc.''' is an American multinational [[conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]] headquartered in [[Mountain View, California]]. It was created through a [[restructuring]] of [[Google]] on October 2, 2015,<ref name=\"sec\">{{cite web |url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1652044/000119312515336577/d82837d8k12b.htm |title=SEC Filing (Form 8-K) by Alphabet Inc. |publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission]] |date=October 2, 2015}}</ref> and became the parent company of Google and several former Google [[Subsidiary|subsidiaries]].<ref name=\"aol\">{{cite web |title=Google to be part of new holding company, 'Alphabet' |url=https://www.aol.com/article/2015/08/10/google-to-be-part-of-new-holding-company-alphabet/21220854/ |accessdate=August 11, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"gIsForGoogle\">{{cite web |url=https://googleblog.blogspot.com/2015/08/google-alphabet.html |title=G is for Google |publisher=Google Official Blog |last1=Page |first1=Larry |accessdate=August 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnet.com/news/google-restructures-into-alphabet-soup-of-businesses/|title=Google creates new parent company called Alphabet|date=August 10, 2015|publisher=CNET|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150917083700/https://www.cnet.com/news/google-restructures-into-alphabet-soup-of-businesses/|archive-date=September 17, 2015|url-status = live|accessdate=September 19, 2015}}</ref> The two founders of Google assumed executive roles in the new company, with [[Larry Page]] serving as CEO and [[Sergey Brin]] as president.<ref name=\"bloomberg2015\">{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2015-08-10/google-to-adopt-new-holding-structure-under-name-alphabet-|title=Google Creates New Company Called Alphabet, Restructures Stock|last1=Womack|first1=Brian|date=August 10, 2015|accessdate=August 10, 2015|agency=Bloomberg}}</ref> Alphabet is the [[List of largest technology companies by revenue|world's fourth-largest technology company]] by revenue and one of the [[List of public corporations by market capitalization|world's most valuable companies]].<ref name=\"Fortune\">{{cite news | url=http://beta.fortune.com/global500/list/filtered?sector=Technology | title=Top 50 Global Technology Companies | publisher=Fortune Global 500 | access-date=June 4, 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170126084151/http://beta.fortune.com/global500/list/filtered?sector=Technology | archive-date=January 26, 2017 | url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Alphabet|url=https://www.forbes.com/companies/alphabet/|work=Forbes|accessdate=June 6, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe establishment of Alphabet was prompted by a desire to make the core Google business \"cleaner and more accountable\" while allowing greater autonomy to group companies that operate in businesses other than Internet services.<ref name=\"gIsForGoogle\" /><ref name=\"wire-2015-new-company\">{{cite journal|last1=Metz|first1=Cade|date=August 10, 2015|title=A New Company Called Alphabet Now Owns Google|url=https://www.wired.com/2015/08/new-company-called-alphabet-owns-google/|journal=[[Wired (website)|Wired]]|accessdate=August 13, 2015}}</ref> Page and Brin announced their resignation from their executive posts in December 2019, with the CEO role to be filled by [[Sundar Pichai]], also the CEO of Google. Page and Brin remain co-founders, employees, board members, and [[controlling interest|controlling shareholders]] of Alphabet Inc.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/jilliandonfro/2019/12/03/larry-page-steps-down-as-ceo-of-google-parent-alphabet/|title=Larry Page Steps Down As CEO Of Alphabet|last=Donfro|first=Jillian|date=December 3, 2019|website=Forbes|access-date=December 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== History ==\nOn August 10, 2015, [[Google|Google Inc.]] announced plans to create a new public [[holding company]], Alphabet Inc. Google CEO [[Larry Page]] made this announcement in a blog post on Google's official blog.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://money.cnn.com/2015/08/10/technology/alphabet-google/index.html|title=Meet Google Alphabet \u2013 Google's new parent company|last=Kelly|first=Heather|date=August 10, 2015|website=CNNMoney|access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref> Alphabet would be created to restructure Google by moving subsidiaries from Google to Alphabet, narrowing Google's scope. The company would consist of Google as well as other businesses including [[X (company)|X Development]], [[Calico (company)|Calico]], [[Google Nest|Nest]], [[Verily]], Fiber, [[Makani (company)|Makani]], [[CapitalG]], and [[GV (company)|GV]].<ref name=\"bloomberg2015\" /><ref>{{cite journal |title=What Google, I Mean Alphabet, Looks Like Now |url=https://www.wired.com/2015/08/google-mean-alphabet-looks-like-now/ |accessdate=August 10, 2015 |date=August 10, 2015 |first=Julia |last=Greenberg |journal=[[Wired (website)|Wired]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=What is Alphabet, Google's new company? |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/what-is-alphabet-googles-new-company-2015-8 |accessdate=August 10, 2015 |work=Business Insider}}</ref> [[Sundar Pichai]], Product Chief, became the new CEO of Google, replacing [[Larry Page]], who transitioned to the role of running Alphabet, along with Google co-founder Sergey Brin.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/google-creates-new-company-alphabet-1439240645 |title=Google Creates Parent Company Called Alphabet in Restructuring |last=Chen |first=Angela |date=August 10, 2015 |work=The Wall Street Journal |accessdate=August 10, 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT_2015_Dougherty\">{{cite news |title=Google to Reorganize in Move to Keep Its Lead as an Innovator |first=Conor |last=Dougherty |date=August 10, 2015 |accessdate=August 10, 2015 |work=The New York Times |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/08/11/technology/google-alphabet-restructuring.html}}</ref>\n\nIn his announcement, Page described the planned holding company as follows:<ref name=\"gIsForGoogle\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |title=Google's Larry Page explains the new Alphabet |url=https://www.cnet.com/news/googles-larry-page-explains-the-new-alphabet/ |publisher=CNET |accessdate=September 19, 2015}}</ref>\n{{quote|Alphabet is mostly a collection of companies. The largest of which, of course, is Google. This newer Google is a bit slimmed down, with the companies that are pretty far afield of our main internet products contained in Alphabet instead. ... Fundamentally, we believe this allows us more management scale, as we can run things independently that aren't very related.}}\n\nPage says the motivation behind the reorganization is to make Google \"cleaner and more accountable and better\". He also said he wanted to improve \"the transparency and oversight of what we're doing\", and to allow greater control of unrelated companies.<ref name=\"gIsForGoogle\" /><ref name=\"wire-2015-new-company\" />\n\nFormer executive Eric Schmidt (now Technical Advisor) revealed in the conference in 2017 the inspiration for this structure came from Warren Buffett and his management structure of Berkshire Hathaway a decade ago.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://markets.businessinsider.com/news/stocks/google-founders-modeled-alphabet-warren-buffett-berkshire-hathaway-2019-12-1028737463|title=Google's founders came up with the Alphabet model after meeting Warren Buffett {{!}} Markets Insider|last=GmbH|first=finanzen net|website=Business Insider|access-date=December 5, 2019}}</ref> Schmidt said it was he who encouraged Page and Brin to meet with Buffett in Omaha to see how Berkshire Hathaway was a holding company made of subsidiaries with strong CEOs who were trusted to run their businesses.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nBefore it became a subsidiary of Alphabet, Google Inc. was first structured as the owner of Alphabet. The roles were reversed after a placeholder subsidiary was created for the ownership of Alphabet, at which point the newly formed subsidiary was merged with Google. Google's stock was then converted to Alphabet's stock. Under the [[Delaware General Corporation Law]] (where Alphabet is incorporated), a holding company reorganization such as this can be done without a vote of shareholders, as this reorganization was.<ref name=\"SEC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1288776/000128877615000039/a20150810form8-k.htm|title=Google Inc. filing with the SEC, Form 8-K|date=August 10, 2015|publisher=[[United States Securities and Exchange Commission]]|accessdate=August 11, 2015}}</ref> The restructuring process was completed on October 2, 2015.<ref name=\"sec\" /> Alphabet retains Google Inc.'s stock price history and continues to trade under Google Inc.'s former ticker symbols \"GOOG\" and \"GOOGL\"; both classes of stock are components of major [[stock market index|stock market indices]] such as the [[S&P 500]] and [[NASDAQ-100]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/GOOGL/|title=GOOGL : Summary for Alphabet Inc.|publisher=Yahoo! Finance|access-date=December 4, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn December 3, 2019, Page and Brin jointly announced that they would step down from their respective roles, remaining as employees and still the majority vote on the board of directors. [[Sundar Pichai]], the CEO of Google, is to assume the CEO role at Alphabet while retaining the same at Google.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/12/03/larry-page-steps-down-as-ceo-of-alphabet.html|title=Larry Page steps down as CEO of Alphabet, Sundar Pichai to take over|last=Feiner|first=Lauren|date=December 3, 2019|publisher=CNBC|access-date=December 3, 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Structure ==\nAlphabet's largest subsidiary is Google. Its other subsidiaries include [[Calico (company)|Calico]], [[DeepMind]], [[GV (company)|GV]], [[Google Capital|CapitalG]], [[X (company)|X]], [[Google Fiber]], [[Makani (company)|Makani]], [[Sidewalk Labs]], [[Verily Life Sciences|Verily]], [[Waymo]], [[Wing (company)|Wing]] and [[Loon LLC|Loon]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180719182259/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/technology-44886803|title=Google's Loon brings internet-by-balloon to Kenya \u2013 BBC News|date=July 19, 2018|website=web.archive.org|access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/alphabet-google-company-list-2017-4|title=All the companies and divisions under Google's parent company, Alphabet|last=Hartmans|first=Avery|website=Business Insider|access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/11/21133398/google-jigsaw-waymo-nest-brin-page-alphabet|title=Alphabet has moved technology incubator Jigsaw under Google management \u2013 The Verge|date=February 11, 2020|website=The Verge|access-date=February 20, 2020}}</ref> {{as of|2017|September|1|df=US}}, their equity is held by a subsidiary known as '''XXVI Holdings, Inc.''' (referring to the Roman numeral of 26, the number of letters in the alphabet), so that they can be valued and legally separated from Google. At the same time, it was announced that Google will be reorganized as a [[limited liability company]], Google LLC.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2017-09-01/alphabet-wraps-up-reorganization-with-a-new-company-called-xxvi |title=Alphabet Finishes Reorganization With New XXVI Company |date=September 1, 2017 |publisher=Bloomberg L.P.|access-date=September 2, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/09/04/google-parent-alphabet-forms-holding-company-xxvi-to-complete-2015-corporate-reorganization/|title=Google parent Alphabet forms holding company, XXVI, to complete 2015 corporate reorganization|website=TechCrunch|access-date=May 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\n[[Eric Schmidt]] said at an [[Internet Association]] event in 2015 that there may eventually be more than 26 Alphabet subsidiaries. He also said that he was currently meeting with the CEOs of the current and proposed Alphabet subsidiaries. He said, \"You'll see a lot coming.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2015/10/13/11619552/eric-schmidt-get-ready-for-a-lot-more-alphabet-companies|title=Eric Schmidt: Get Ready for 'a Lot' More Alphabet Companies|last1=Bergen|first1=Mark|date=October 13, 2015|website=Vox|publisher=Re/code|accessdate=October 19, 2015}}</ref>\n\nWhile many companies or divisions formerly a part of Google became subsidiaries of Alphabet, Google remains the umbrella company for Alphabet's Internet-related businesses. These include widely used products and services long associated with Google, such as the [[Android (operating system)|Android mobile operating system]], YouTube, and [[Google Search]], which remain direct components of Google.<ref name=\"bloomberg2015\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Google's new Alphabet, from A to Z (pictures) |url=https://www.cnet.com/pictures/googles-new-alphabet-from-a-to-z/ |publisher=CNET |accessdate=August 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\nFormer subsidiaries include [[Nest Labs]], which was merged into Google in February 2018<ref>{{cite web |url=https://arstechnica.com/gadgets/2018/02/nest-is-done-as-a-standalone-alphabet-company-merges-with-google/ |title=Nest is done as a standalone Alphabet company, merges with Google |first=Ron |last=Amadeo |date=February 7, 2018 |website=Ars Technica}}</ref> and [[Chronicle (company)|Chronicle]] which was merged with Google Cloud in June 2019.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://cloud.google.com/blog/topics/inside-google-cloud/the-security-moonshot-joins-google-cloud |title=Google Cloud + Chronicle: The security moonshot joins Google Cloud |first=Thomas |last=Kurian |date=June 27, 2019 |website=Inside Google Cloud}}</ref>\n\n== Corporate identity ==\nPage explained the origin of the company's name:<ref name=\":0\" />\n{{quote|We liked the name Alphabet because it means a collection of letters that represent language, one of humanity's most important innovations, and is the core of how we index with Google search! We also like that it means alpha\u2011bet ([[Alpha (finance)|Alpha]] is investment return above benchmark), which we strive for!}}\n\nIn a 2018 talk, Schmidt disclosed that the original inspiration for the name came from the location of the then Google Hamburg office's street address: {{Interlanguage link|ABC-Stra\u00dfe|de}}.<ref>{{cite web |title=Wie die Hamburger ABC-Stra\u00dfe Google pr\u00e4gte |url=https://www.abendblatt.de/hamburg/hamburg-mitte/article215905959/Wie-die-Hamburger-ABC-Strasse-Google-praegte.html |website=abendblatt.de |accessdate=November 30, 2018|date=November 29, 2018 }}</ref>\n\nAlphabet has chosen the domain abc.xyz with the [[.xyz]] [[top-level domain]] (TLD), which was introduced in 2014. It does not own the domain alphabet.com, which is owned by a [[fleet management]] division of [[BMW]]. BMW has said that it is \"necessary to examine the legal trademark implications\" of the proposals. Additionally, it does not own the domain abc.com, which is the promoted domain of the [[The Walt Disney Company|Disney]]-owned [[American Broadcasting Company]] (abc.com redirects to a subdomain of [[go.com]], through which most of Disney's sites are hosted).<ref>{{cite news |last1=Davidson |first1=Lauren |title=Google unveils Alphabet... but that's already trademarked by BMW |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/finance/newsbysector/mediatechnologyandtelecoms/11797616/Google-unveils-Alphabet...-but-thats-already-trademarked-by-BMW.html |website=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |accessdate=August 12, 2015|date=August 11, 2015 }}</ref><ref name=\"tc-alphabet-bmw\">{{cite news |last1=Lardinois |first1=Frederic |title=Google Is Now Alphabet, But It Doesn't Own Alphabet.com |url=https://techcrunch.com/2015/08/10/google-is-now-alphabet-but-it-doesnt-own-alphabet-com/ |accessdate=August 11, 2015 |work=[[TechCrunch]] |publisher=AOL Inc. |date=August 10, 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe website features an [[Easter egg (media)|Easter egg]] in the paragraph where Larry Page writes, \"Sergey and I are seriously in the business of starting new things. Alphabet will also include our [[Google X Labs|X lab]], which incubates new efforts like [[X (company)#Wing|Wing]], our [[drone delivery]] effort. We are also stoked about growing our investment arms, Ventures and Capital, as part of this new structure.\" The period after \"drone delivery effort\" is a [[hyperlink]] to \"hooli.xyz\",<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.hooli.xyz/#inspiration |title=hooli}}</ref> a reference to the television series ''[[Silicon Valley (TV series)|Silicon Valley]]''.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/tv-and-radio/2015/aug/11/google-silicon-valley-spinal-tap-tech |date=August 12, 2015 |accessdate=February 28, 2016 |title=Google's hooli.xyz Easter egg proves Silicon Valley is tech's own Spinal Tap |first=David |last=Stubbs | authorlink = David Stubbs|work=[[The Guardian]]}}</ref>\n\n== Revenue ==\nAs per its 2017 annual report, 86% of Alphabet's revenues came from performance advertising (through user clicks using [[Adsense]] and [[Google Ads]]) and brand advertising.<ref name=\"agm2017\">{{cite book |title=Annual report 2017 |date=March 2, 2018 |publisher=Alphabet investor relations |pages=2, 3, 5, 6 |url=https://abc.xyz/investor |accessdate=December 3, 2018}}</ref> Of these, 53% came from its international operations. This translated to a total revenue of US$110,855&nbsp;million in 2017 and a net income of US$12,662&nbsp;million.\n\nOn February 1, 2016, Alphabet Inc. surpassed [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] to become the world's most valuable publicly traded company until February 3, 2016, when Apple surged back over Alphabet to retake the position. Experts cited Apple's lack of innovation as well as increasing Chinese competition as reasons for the poor performance.<ref name=\"alphabet-most-valuable\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2016/02/01/google-passes-apple-as-most-valuable-company.html|title=Google passes Apple as most valuable company|last1=Levy|first1=Ari|website=[[CNBC]].com|publisher=[[NBCUniversal]]|accessdate=February 1, 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"apple-most-valuable\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/money/markets/2016/02/03/apple-not-going-down-easy/79763410/|title=Apple not going down easy as it overtakes Google parent Alphabet|last1=Krantz|first1=Matt|website=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=February 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n{{as of|2019|||df=}}, Alphabet is ranked No. 15 on the [[Fortune 500]] rankings of the largest United States corporations by total revenue.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://fortune.com/fortune500/2019/search/|title=Fortune 500|website=[[Fortune (magazine)|Fortune]]|url-status=live|access-date=November 9, 2018}}</ref>\n\nOn January 16, 2020, Alphabet became the fourth US company to reach a $1 [[trillion]] market value<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/alphabet-becomes-fourth-u-s-company-to-ever-reach-1-trillion-market-value-11579208802|title=Alphabet Becomes Fourth U.S. Company to Reach $1 Trillion Market Value|last=Ramkumar|first=Amrith|website=The Wall Street Journal|access-date=January 19, 2020}}</ref> entering the [[List of public corporations by market capitalization|Trillion dollar companies club]] for the first time.\n\n== Investments and acquisitions ==\n\n=== Investments ===\nIn November 2017, Alphabet Inc. led a Series A round of $71&nbsp;million along with [[Andreessen Horowitz]] and [[20th Century Fox]] in music startup [[UnitedMasters]], founded by [[Steve Stoute]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://techcrunch.com/2017/11/15/united-masters/ |title=With $70M from Alphabet, UnitedMasters replaces record labels |last=Constine |first=Josh |work=TechCrunch|access-date=December 4, 2017 }}</ref>\n\n=== Acquisitions ===\n{{Main|List of mergers and acquisitions by Alphabet}}\nAn analysis of the company's investments in 2017 suggested that it was the most active investor in that period, outdoing the capital arm of [[Intel]] and also its own best customer. Alphabet, Inc. acquired seven of its own capital-backed startups in the 2017 financial year, with [[Cisco]] second having acquired six of the company's previous investments.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://techcrunch.com/2018/02/17/a-peek-inside-alphabets-investing-universe/ |title=A peek inside Alphabet's investing universe |work=[[Techcrunch]] |date=February 17, 2018}}</ref>\n\nFlatiron Health, a startup founded by two former Google employees and backed by Alphabet, Inc., announced that it was to be acquired by health conglomerate [[Hoffmann-La Roche]] for $1.8&nbsp;billion. The company provides electronic medical records and analysis to identify improved treatments for [[oncology]] patients.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/02/15/roche-buying-flatiron-health-backed-by-alphabet.html |title=Alphabet-backed Flatiron Health is being acquired by Roche |publisher=CNBC |first=Christina |last=Farr |date=February 15, 2018| access-date= March 28, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Lawsuit==\nAlphabet Inc. sued [[Uber]] over technology similar to Alphabet's proprietary self-driving car technology.{{when|date=February 2020}} Alphabet's [[autonomous vehicle]] technology has been under development for a decade by Alphabet's [[Waymo]] (self-driving vehicle division). The [[proprietary software|proprietary technology]] is related to 14,000 documents believed to have been downloaded and stolen by a former Waymo engineer, subsequently employed by Uber.<ref name=\"suit\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-uber-alphabet-lawsuit-idUSKBN18Q2CW|title=Uber fires self-driving car chief at center of court case|last1=Sage|first1=Alexandria|date=May 30, 2017|accessdate=May 30, 2017|agency=Reuters}}</ref><ref name=\"selfdrive\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/05/30/technology/uber-anthony-levandowski.html|title=Uber Fires Former Google Engineer at Heart of Self-Driving Dispute|last1=Isaac|first1=Mike|date=May 30, 2017|work=[[The New York Times]]|accessdate=May 30, 2017|last2=Wakabayashi|first2=Daisuke}}</ref> The lawsuit was settled in February 2018, with Uber agreeing not to use the self-driving technology in dispute and also agreed to provide [[Waymo]] with an equity stake of 0.34%, equating to around $245&nbsp;million at the firm's early 2018 value.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/02/09/uber-waymo-lawsuit-settlement.html|title=Uber settles dispute with Alphabet's self driving car unit|last1=Balakrishnan|first1=Anita|date=February 9, 2018|publisher=CNBC|last2=D'Onfro|first2=Jillian|last3=Bosa|first3=Deirdre|last4=Zaveri|first4=Paayal}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* {{Portal inline|size=tiny|Internet}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Alphabet Inc.}}\n* {{official website}}\n{{Finance links\n| name = Alphabet Inc. (class A)\n| symbol = GOOGL\n| sec_cik = GOOGL\n| yahoo = GOOGL\n| google = GOOGL\n| reuters = GOOGL.O\n| bloomberg = GOOGL:US\n}}\n{{Finance links\n| name = Alphabet Inc. (class C)\n| symbol = GOOG\n| sec_cik = GOOG\n| yahoo = GOOG\n| google = GOOG\n| reuters = GOOG.O\n| bloomberg = GOOG:US\n}}\n\n{{Alphabet Inc.|state=expanded}}\n{{Google Inc.}}\n{{NASDAQ-100}}\n\n[[Category:Alphabet Inc.| ]]\n[[Category:2015 establishments in California]]\n[[Category:American companies established in 2015]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Mountain View, California]]\n[[Category:Companies based in Silicon Valley]]\n[[Category:Companies listed on NASDAQ]]\n[[Category:Computer-related introductions in 2015]]\n[[Category:Conglomerate companies established in 2015]]\n[[Category:Conglomerate companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Google]]\n[[Category:Holding companies established in 2015]]\n[[Category:Holding companies of the United States]]\n[[Category:Multinational companies headquartered in the United States]]\n[[Category:Technology companies based in the San Francisco Bay Area]]\n[[Category:Technology companies established in 2015]]\n[[Category:Video game companies based in California]]\n[[Category:Biotechnology companies of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "103.73.106.250", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Alphabet_Inc."}
{"title_page": "Last Dayz", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Last Dayz\n| cover      = Last Dayz.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Onyx (hip hop group)|Onyx]]\n| album      = [[All We Got Iz Us]]\n| B-side     = All We Got Iz Us\n| released   = October 3, 1995\n| format     = [[12-inch single|12\" single]], [[CD single]], [[Cassette single|cassette]], [[Promotional recording|airplay]]\n| recorded   = 1994\n| studio     = LGK Studios, [[Leonia, New Jersey]]\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[hardcore rap]], [[East Coast hip hop]], [[horrorcore]]\n| length     = 3:32\n| label      = [[JMJ Records]]<br/>[[Rush Associated Labels]]\n| writer     = [[Fredro Starr|Fred Scruggs]]<br/>[[Sticky Fingaz|Kirk Jones]]<br/>[[Sonny Seeza|Tyrone Taylor]]<br/>[[Earl Klugh]]\n| producer   = [[Fredro Starr]]\n| chronology = [[Onyx (group)|Onyx]]\n| prev_title = [[Live!!!]]\n| prev_year  = 1995\n| next_title = [[The Worst (Wu-Tang Clan and Onyx song)|The Worst]]\n| next_year  = 1997\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|S1ThxWzkELk|\"Last Dayz\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Last Dayz'''\" is a song by American hip hop group [[Onyx (hip hop group)|Onyx]]. It was released on October 3, 1995 by [[JMJ Records]] and [[Rush Associated Labels]] as the second single from Onyx's second album, ''[[All We Got Iz Us]]''.\n\nProduced by [[Fredro Starr]], \"Last Dayz\" making it to number 89 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. Instrumental of this song was used in the film [[8 Mile (film)|8 Mile]] for the rap battle between Lotto and B-Rabbit. The song was sampled by more than 10 rap artists including [[Jus Allah]], [[Jedi Mind Tricks]], [[Immortal Technique]], and [[Vinnie Paz]].<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.whosampled.com/Onyx/Last-Dayz/|title=Last Dayz by Onyx| website=whosampled.com |access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the song was re-recorded by Onyx, and released on a compilation album ''Songs of the 90's''.\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video was directed by [[Joseph Kahn]],<ref>{{cite web| url= https://imvdb.com/video/onyx/last-dayz|title=Last Dayz (1995) by Onyx | website=imvdb.com |access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref> Barry Shapiro was a producer of this video. The video was filmed in an Industrial Park, New York City, and was premiered on [[The Box (U.S. TV channel)|The BOX]] on October 20, 1995. The video can be found on the 2008's DVD ''Onyx: 15 Years Of Videos, History And Violence''.\n\n== Incident in Newark ==\n* In 1996, riot breaks out at Onyx's concert during the performance \"Last Dayz\" in [[Newark, New Jersey]]. Fredro Starr told everybody in the audience that, ''they got the power to take over the world. They could do what the fuck they want to do''. When Fredro said that, the whole crowd just got vibrant.<ref>{{Cite web| url= https://www.ozy.com/flashback/the-other-side-of-happy/30629|title=ONYX TAKES YOU TO THE LAST DAYZ (by Datwon Thomas) [March 31, 2014]| website=ozy.com |access-date=2018-10-03}}</ref>\n\n== Appearance in movies ==\n* In 2002, instrumental of this song was used in the film [[8 Mile (film)|8 Mile]] for the rap battle between Lotto and B-Rabbit.<ref>{{Cite web| url= https://www.what-song.com/Movies/Soundtrack/309/8-Mile|title=8 Mile Soundtrack| website=what-song.com |access-date=2018-10-03}}</ref>\n* In 2014, the song appeared in ''The Brodies'', the movie by Jeremy Elkin about skateboarding.<ref>{{Cite web| url= http://www.skatevideosite.com/skatevideos/the-brodies/soundtrack|title=The Brodies (2014)| website=skatevideosite.com |access-date=2018-10-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web| url= https://vimeo.com/85983570|title=The Brodies (2014)| website=vimeo.com |access-date=2018-10-03}}</ref>\n\n== Appearance on television ==\n* In 1995, \"Last Dayz\" was performed live on a daytime [[tabloid talk show]] [[Ricki Lake (TV series)|Ricki Lake]] on December 13, 1995.\n* In 2015, Fredro Starr named \"Last Dayz\" as his favorite Onyx's record during interview with Steve Lobel. He also added that this is [[Kanye West]]'s favorite Onyx's song too.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sVfwpu_NF4A|title=Fredro Starr on South Side Queens, Kanye West, Russia & Last Days| website=youtube.com |access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref>\n* In 2018, Fredro Starr said that \"Last Dayz\" put him on as a bonafide lyricist on [[B-Real]]'s TV brand new episode of ''Once Upon A Rhyme''.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DU0lch-9DDA|title=Fredro Starr (Onyx) - Once Upon A Rhyme - BREAL.TV [September 14, 2018]| website=youtube.com |access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref>\n* In 2018, the song appeared in the [[BET]]'s show \"Rate The Bars\", in the episode with [[EPMD]] aired on July 30, 2018. On each episode of \"Rate The Bars\" rappers rate the bars of their peers without knowing who the lines belong to.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pCNx0F-ZJgc&t=49|title=EPMD Impressed By Lil Skies' \"Lust\"?! + Kodak Black, Lil Xan, Das EFX - Rate The Bars [July 30, 2018]| website=youtube.com |access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref>\n* In 2018, the song \"Last Dayz\" appeared on ''[[The Joe Budden Podcast]]'', episode 180 \"Blessed\" aired on September 21, 2018.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7Yq9HEGS9A4&t=3305|title=The Joe Budden Podcast - Episode 180 - Blessed [September 21, 2018]| website=youtube.com |access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref>\n\n== Cover versions ==\n* In 2003, [[Dead Prez]] teamed up with [[Fredro Starr]] and [[Sticky Fingaz]] to recorded \"Last Days Reloaded\" for Dead Prez's mixtape ''Turn off the Radio: The Mixtape, Vol. 2: Get Free or Die Tryin'''.\n\n== Parodies ==\n* In 2018, videographer Mylo the Cat used the song for his cartoon starring [[Krang]] from [[TMNT]].<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.instagram.com/p/BjdXUFehS4r/|title=Sticky Fingaz as Krang from TMNT rapping the classic \"Last Dayz\" (Video by Mylo the Cat) (2018)| website=instagram.com |access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref>\n\n== Accolades ==\nIn 2018, [[The Boombox]] put the song in their list ''Rap Songs That Sample Aretha Franklin''.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://theboombox.com/aretha-franklin-samples|title=Rap Songs That Sample Aretha Franklin [August 16, 2018]| website=theboombox.com |access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref> In 2018, the song \"Last Dayz\" was included by [[WhoSampled]] in mix ''A Hip Hop Tribute to Aretha Franklin'', dedicated to the memory of the Queen of Soul, [[Aretha Franklin]], who died just under a month ago.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.whosampled.com/news/2018/09/13/a-hip-hop-tribute-to-aretha-franklin-mixed-by-dj-filthy-rich|title=\"A Hip Hop Tribute to Aretha Franklin\" (Mixed by DJ Filthy Rich) [September 13, 2018]| website=whosampled.com |access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Publication\n! Country\n! Accolade\n! Year\n! Rank\n|-\n|''[[The Boombox]]''\n|rowspan=2|[[United States]]\n|''Rap Songs That Sample Aretha Franklin''\n|2018\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|*\n|-\n|''[[WhoSampled]]''\n|''A Hip Hop Tribute to Aretha Franklin''\n|2018\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|*\n|}\n\n==Releases==\n===CD maxi-single track listing===\n#\"Last Dayz\" (LP Version)- 3:32\n#\"All We Got Iz Us\" (Evil Streets) (LP Version) - 4:04\n#\"Walk In New York\" (LP Version)- 4:55\n#\"Last Dayz\" (Radio Version)- 3:32\n#\"All We Got Iz Us\" (Evil Streets) (Radio Version) - 3:53\n#\"Last Dayz\" (Instrumental)- 3:32\n#\"All We Got Iz Us\" (Evil Streets) (Instrumental)- 4:05\n#\"Last Dayz\" (A Cappella)- 3:20\n\n===12\" vinyl single track listing===\n#\"Last Dayz\" (LP Version) - 3:32\n#\"Last Dayz\" (Radio Version) - 3:32\n#\"Last Dayz\" (Instrumental) - 3:32\n#\"Last Dayz\" (A Cappella) - 3:20\n#\"All We Got Iz Us\" (Evil Streets) (LP Version) - 4:04\n#\"All We Got Iz Us\" (Evil Streets) (Radio Version) - 3:53\n#\"All We Got Iz Us\" (Evil Streets) (Instrumental)- 4:05\n#\"All We Got Iz Us\" (Evil Streets) (Acapella) - 3:58\n\n===Cassette single track listing===\n#\"Last Dayz\" (LP