Magazine - October 21, 1995: Hot Dance Music/Maxi-Singles Sales| website=books.google.com |access-date=2019-02-10}}</ref>\n|align=\"left\"|28\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US Top 25 Rap Singles (''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cashbox]]'')<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Cash-Box-IDX/90s/1995/CB-1995-11-25-OCR-Page-0013.pdf|title=Top 25 Rap Singles (Cashbox) November 25, 1995| website=americanradiohistory.com |access-date=2018-11-17}}</ref>\n|align=\"left\"|12\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US Gavin Rap Retail (''[[Gavin Report]]'')<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Gavin-IDX/IDX/90s/95/Gavin-1995-11-10-OCR-Page-0032.pdf|title=Gavin Rap Retail (Gavin Report) November 10, 1995| website=americanradiohistory.com |access-date=2018-11-17}}</ref>\n|align=\"left\"|12\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US Gavin Rap (''[[Gavin Report]]'')<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Gavin-IDX/IDX/90s/95/Gavin-1995-12-08-OCR-Page-0018.pdf|title=Gavin Rap (Gavin Report) December 8, 1995| website=americanradiohistory.com |access-date=2018-11-17}}</ref>\n|align=\"left\"|19\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[https://genius.com/Onyx-last-dayz-lyrics Last Dayz at RapGenius]\n*[https://www.discogs.com/Onyx-Last-Dayz/master/63264 Last Dayz at Discogs]\n\n{{Onyx}}\n\n[[Category:1995 singles]]\n[[Category:1995 songs]]\n[[Category:Onyx (group) songs]]\n[[Category:JMJ Records singles]]\n[[Category:Def Jam Recordings singles]]\n[[Category:Horrorcore songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Last Dayz\n| cover      = Last Dayz.jpg\n| alt        =\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Onyx (hip hop group)|Onyx]]\n| album      = [[All We Got Iz Us]]\n| B-side     = All We Got Iz Us\n| released   = October 3, 1995\n| format     = [[12-inch single|12\" single]], [[CD single]], [[Cassette single|cassette]], [[Promotional recording|airplay]]\n| recorded   = 1995\n| studio     = LGK Studios, [[Leonia, New Jersey]]\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[hardcore rap]], [[East Coast hip hop]], [[horrorcore]]\n| length     = 3:32\n| label      = [[JMJ Records]]<br/>[[Rush Associated Labels]]\n| writer     = [[Fredro Starr|Fred Scruggs]]<br/>[[Sticky Fingaz|Kirk Jones]]<br/>[[Sonny Seeza|Tyrone Taylor]]<br/>[[Earl Klugh]]\n| producer   = [[Agallah & Fredro Starr]]\n| chronology = [[Onyx (group)|Onyx]]\n| prev_title = [[Live!!!]]\n| prev_year  = 1995\n| next_title = [[The Worst (Wu-Tang Clan and Onyx song)|The Worst]]\n| next_year  = 1997\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|S1ThxWzkELk|\"Last Dayz\"}}}}\n}}\n\n\"'''Last Dayz'''\" is a song by American hip hop group [[Onyx (hip hop group)|Onyx]]. It was released on October 3, 1995 by [[JMJ Records]] and [[Rush Associated Labels]] as the second single from Onyx's second album, ''[[All We Got Iz Us]]''.\n\nProduced by [[Agallah & Fredro Starr]], \"Last Dayz\" making it to number 89 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]. Instrumental of this song was used in the film [[8 Mile (film)|8 Mile]] for the rap battle between Lotto and B-Rabbit. The song was sampled by more than 10 rap artists including [[Jus Allah]], [[Jedi Mind Tricks]], [[Immortal Technique]], and [[Vinnie Paz]].<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.whosampled.com/Onyx/Last-Dayz/|title=Last Dayz by Onyx| website=whosampled.com |access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the song was re-recorded by Onyx, and released on a compilation album ''Songs of the 90's''.\n\n==Music video==\nThe music video was directed by [[Joseph Kahn]],<ref>{{cite web| url= https://imvdb.com/video/onyx/last-dayz|title=Last Dayz (1995) by Onyx | website=imvdb.com |access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref> Barry Shapiro was a producer of this video. The video was filmed in an Industrial Park, New York City, and was premiered on [[The Box (U.S. TV channel)|The BOX]] on October 20, 1995. The video can be found on the 2008's DVD ''Onyx: 15 Years Of Videos, History And Violence''.\n\n== Incident in Newark ==\n* In 1996, riot breaks out at Onyx's concert during the performance \"Last Dayz\" in [[Newark, New Jersey]]. Fredro Starr told everybody in the audience that, ''they got the power to take over the world. They could do what the fuck they want to do''. When Fredro said that, the whole crowd just got vibrant.<ref>{{Cite web| url= https://www.ozy.com/flashback/the-other-side-of-happy/30629|title=ONYX TAKES YOU TO THE LAST DAYZ (by Datwon Thomas) [March 31, 2014]| website=ozy.com |access-date=2018-10-03}}</ref>\n\n== Appearance in movies ==\n* In 2002, instrumental of this song was used in the film [[8 Mile (film)|8 Mile]] for the rap battle between Lotto and B-Rabbit.<ref>{{Cite web| url= https://www.what-song.com/Movies/Soundtrack/309/8-Mile|title=8 Mile Soundtrack| website=what-song.com |access-date=2018-10-03}}</ref>\n* In 2014, the song appeared in ''The Brodies'', the movie by Jeremy Elkin about skateboarding.<ref>{{Cite web| url= http://www.skatevideosite.com/skatevideos/the-brodies/soundtrack|title=The Brodies (2014)| website=skatevideosite.com |access-date=2018-10-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web| url= https://vimeo.com/85983570|title=The Brodies (2014)| website=vimeo.com |access-date=2018-10-03}}</ref>\n\n== Appearance on television ==\n* In 1995, \"Last Dayz\" was performed live on a daytime [[tabloid talk show]] [[Ricki Lake (TV series)|Ricki Lake]] on December 13, 1995.\n* In 2015, Fredro Starr named \"Last Dayz\" as his favorite Onyx's record during interview with Steve Lobel. He also added that this is [[Kanye West]]'s favorite Onyx's song too.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sVfwpu_NF4A|title=Fredro Starr on South Side Queens, Kanye West, Russia & Last Days| website=youtube.com |access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref>\n* In 2018, Fredro Starr said that \"Last Dayz\" put him on as a bonafide lyricist on [[B-Real]]'s TV brand new episode of ''Once Upon A Rhyme''.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DU0lch-9DDA|title=Fredro Starr (Onyx) - Once Upon A Rhyme - BREAL.TV [September 14, 2018]| website=youtube.com |access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref>\n* In 2018, the song appeared in the [[BET]]'s show \"Rate The Bars\", in the episode with [[EPMD]] aired on July 30, 2018. On each episode of \"Rate The Bars\" rappers rate the bars of their peers without knowing who the lines belong to.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pCNx0F-ZJgc&t=49|title=EPMD Impressed By Lil Skies' \"Lust\"?! + Kodak Black, Lil Xan, Das EFX - Rate The Bars [July 30, 2018]| website=youtube.com |access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref>\n* In 2018, the song \"Last Dayz\" appeared on ''[[The Joe Budden Podcast]]'', episode 180 \"Blessed\" aired on September 21, 2018.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=7Yq9HEGS9A4&t=3305|title=The Joe Budden Podcast - Episode 180 - Blessed [September 21, 2018]| website=youtube.com |access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref>\n\n== Cover versions ==\n* In 2003, [[Dead Prez]] teamed up with [[Fredro Starr]] and [[Sticky Fingaz]] to recorded \"Last Days Reloaded\" for Dead Prez's mixtape ''Turn off the Radio: The Mixtape, Vol. 2: Get Free or Die Tryin'''.\n\n== Parodies ==\n* In 2018, videographer Mylo the Cat used the song for his cartoon starring [[Krang]] from [[TMNT]].<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.instagram.com/p/BjdXUFehS4r/|title=Sticky Fingaz as Krang from TMNT rapping the classic \"Last Dayz\" (Video by Mylo the Cat) (2018)| website=instagram.com |access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref>\n\n== Accolades ==\nIn 2018, [[The Boombox]] put the song in their list ''Rap Songs That Sample Aretha Franklin''.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://theboombox.com/aretha-franklin-samples|title=Rap Songs That Sample Aretha Franklin [August 16, 2018]| website=theboombox.com |access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref> In 2018, the song \"Last Dayz\" was included by [[WhoSampled]] in mix ''A Hip Hop Tribute to Aretha Franklin'', dedicated to the memory of the Queen of Soul, [[Aretha Franklin]], who died just under a month ago.<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.whosampled.com/news/2018/09/13/a-hip-hop-tribute-to-aretha-franklin-mixed-by-dj-filthy-rich|title=\"A Hip Hop Tribute to Aretha Franklin\" (Mixed by DJ Filthy Rich) [September 13, 2018]| website=whosampled.com |access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref>\n\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Publication\n! Country\n! Accolade\n! Year\n! Rank\n|-\n|''[[The Boombox]]''\n|rowspan=2|[[United States]]\n|''Rap Songs That Sample Aretha Franklin''\n|2018\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|*\n|-\n|''[[WhoSampled]]''\n|''A Hip Hop Tribute to Aretha Franklin''\n|2018\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|*\n|}\n\n==Releases==\n===CD maxi-single track listing===\n#\"Last Dayz\" (LP Version)- 3:32\n#\"All We Got Iz Us\" (Evil Streets) (LP Version) - 4:04\n#\"Walk In New York\" (LP Version)- 4:55\n#\"Last Dayz\" (Radio Version)- 3:32\n#\"All We Got Iz Us\" (Evil Streets) (Radio Version) - 3:53\n#\"Last Dayz\" (Instrumental)- 3:32\n#\"All We Got Iz Us\" (Evil Streets) (Instrumental)- 4:05\n#\"Last Dayz\" (A Cappella)- 3:20\n\n===12\" vinyl single track listing===\n#\"Last Dayz\" (LP Version) - 3:32\n#\"Last Dayz\" (Radio Version) - 3:32\n#\"Last Dayz\" (Instrumental) - 3:32\n#\"Last Dayz\" (A Cappella) - 3:20\n#\"All We Got Iz Us\" (Evil Streets) (LP Version) - 4:04\n#\"All We Got Iz Us\" (Evil Streets) (Radio Version) - 3:53\n#\"All We Got Iz Us\" (Evil Streets) (Instrumental)- 4:05\n#\"All We Got Iz Us\" (Evil Streets) (Acapella) - 3:58\n\n===Cassette single track listing===\n#\"Last Dayz\" (LP Version)- 3:32\n#\"All We Got Iz Us\" (Evil Streets) (LP Version) - 4:04\n#\"Walk In New York\" (LP Version)- 4:55\n\n==Samples==\n*\"Love Lips\" by [[Bob James (musician)|Bob James]] and [[Earl Klugh]]\n*\"A Song for You\" by [[Aretha Franklin]]\n*\"Outside Love\" by Brethren\n*Dialogue from [[Menace II Society]]\n\n== Personnel ==\n* Onyx - performer, vocals\n* Fredro Starr - performer, vocals\n* Sticky Fingaz - performer, vocals\n* Sonee Seeza - performer, vocals, scratches (\"Walk In New York\")\n* Flamboyant - scratches (\"Walk In New York\")\n* Panama P.I. - additional vocals (\"All We Got Iz Us\")\n* Jason Mizell -  executive producer\n* Randy Allen -  executive producer\n* Jaye Battle - project coordinator\n* Don Elliot - engineer\n* Tony Dawsey - mastering\n\n==Charts==\n===Weekly charts===\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n!align=\"left\"|Chart\n!align=\"left\"|Position\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]]<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.billboard.com/music/onyx/chart-history/hot-100/song/38620|title=Hot 100 (Billboard) December 2nd, 1995| website=billboard.com |access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref>\n|align=\"left\"|89\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US [[Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Singles & Tracks]] ([[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']])<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.billboard.com/music/onyx/chart-history/r-b-hip-hop-songs/song/38620|title=Hot R&B/Hip-Hop Songs (Billboard) November 4th, 1995| website=billboard.com |access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref>\n|align=\"left\"|61\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US [[Hot Rap Singles]] ([[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']])<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.billboard.com/music/onyx/chart-history/rap-song/song/38620|title=Hot Rap Songs (Billboard) November 4th, 1995| website=billboard.com |access-date=2018-10-02}}</ref>\n|align=\"left\"|10\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US [[Hot Dance Music/Maxi-Singles Sales]] ([[Billboard (magazine)|''Billboard'']])<ref>{{cite web| url= https://books.google.com/books?id=mw4EAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA35|title=Billboard Magazine - October 21, 1995: Hot Dance Music/Maxi-Singles Sales| website=books.google.com |access-date=2019-02-10}}</ref>\n|align=\"left\"|28\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US Top 25 Rap Singles (''[[Cashbox (magazine)|Cashbox]]'')<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Cash-Box-IDX/90s/1995/CB-1995-11-25-OCR-Page-0013.pdf|title=Top 25 Rap Singles (Cashbox) November 25, 1995| website=americanradiohistory.com |access-date=2018-11-17}}</ref>\n|align=\"left\"|12\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US Gavin Rap Retail (''[[Gavin Report]]'')<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Gavin-IDX/IDX/90s/95/Gavin-1995-11-10-OCR-Page-0032.pdf|title=Gavin Rap Retail (Gavin Report) November 10, 1995| website=americanradiohistory.com |access-date=2018-11-17}}</ref>\n|align=\"left\"|12\n|-\n|align=\"left\"|US Gavin Rap (''[[Gavin Report]]'')<ref>{{cite web| url= https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Music/Archive-Gavin-IDX/IDX/90s/95/Gavin-1995-12-08-OCR-Page-0018.pdf|title=Gavin Rap (Gavin Report) December 8, 1995| website=americanradiohistory.com |access-date=2018-11-17}}</ref>\n|align=\"left\"|19\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n\n<references />\n\n==External links==\n*[https://genius.com/Onyx-last-dayz-lyrics Last Dayz at RapGenius]\n*[https://www.discogs.com/Onyx-Last-Dayz/master/63264 Last Dayz at Discogs]\n\n{{Onyx}}\n\n[[Category:1995 singles]]\n[[Category:1995 songs]]\n[[Category:Onyx (group) songs]]\n[[Category:JMJ Records singles]]\n[[Category:Def Jam Recordings singles]]\n[[Category:Horrorcore songs]]\n", "name_user": "Felix Montana", "label": "safe", "comment": "Agallah is not credited.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Last_Dayz"}
{"title_page": "The Sister", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Sister\n| type       = Album\n| artist     = [[Marissa Nadler]]\n| cover      = Marissanadler-thesister.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = May 29, 2012\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Folk music|Folk]], [[dream pop]]\n| length     =\n| label      = Box of Cedar Records\n| producer   = Brian McTear\n| prev_title = [[Marissa Nadler (album)|Marissa Nadler]]\n| prev_year  = 2011\n| next_title = [[July (Marissa Nadler album)|July]]\n| next_year  = 2014\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 71/100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/the-sister/marissa-nadler|title=The Sister by Marissa Nadler|publisher=|accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref>\n|rev1 = ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]''\n|rev1Score = (9/10)<ref name=\"pastea\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2012/05/marissa-nadler-the-sister.html|title=Marissa Nadler: The Sister|publisher=PasteMagazine.com |date=2012-05-30 |accessdate=2012-05-31}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''The Sister''''' is [[Marissa Nadler]]'s sixth studio album. It was released on May 29, 2012, by Box of Cedar Records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2012/02/check-out-marissa-nadler-the-wrecking-ball-company/|title=Check Out: Marissa Nadler \u2013 \u201cThe Wrecking Ball Company\u201d|date=14 February 2012|publisher=|accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref> Nadler announced the album on her Facebook page as a \"sister album\" to her 2011 [[Marissa Nadler (album)|eponymous]] album. The album was dubbed by ''[[Paste Magazine]]'' an \"impressive concoction of stark minimalism.\"<ref name=\"pastea\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n# \"The Wrecking Ball Company\"\n# \"Love Again, There Is a Fire\"\n# \"Christine\"\n# \"Apostle\"\n# \"Constantine\"\n# \"To a Road, Love\"\n# \"In a Little Town\"\n# \"Your Heart Is a Twisted Vine\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.marissanadler.com/ Marissa Nadler Official Site]\n{{Marissa Nadler}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sister, The}}\n[[Category:2012 albums]]\n[[Category:Marissa Nadler albums]]\n\n\n{{2010s-folk-album-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album\n| name       = The Sister\n| type       = Album\n| artist     = [[Marissa Nadler]]\n| cover      = Marissanadler-thesister.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = May 29, 2012\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Folk music|Folk]], [[dream pop]]\n| length     =\n| label      = Box of Cedar Records\n| producer   = Brian McTear\n| prev_title = [[Marissa Nadler (album)|Marissa Nadler]]\n| prev_year  = 2011\n| next_title = [[July (Marissa Nadler album)|July]]\n| next_year  = 2014\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| MC = 71/100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/music/the-sister/marissa-nadler|title=The Sister by Marissa Nadler|publisher=|accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref>\n|rev1 = ''[[Paste (magazine)|Paste]]''\n|rev1Score = (9/10)<ref name=\"pastea\">{{cite web|url=http://www.pastemagazine.com/articles/2012/05/marissa-nadler-the-sister.html|title=Marissa Nadler: The Sister|publisher=PasteMagazine.com |date=2012-05-30 |accessdate=2012-05-31}}</ref>\n}}\n'''''The Sister''''' is [[Marissa Nadler]]'s sixth studio album. It was released on May 29, 2012 by Box of Cedar Records.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://consequenceofsound.net/2012/02/check-out-marissa-nadler-the-wrecking-ball-company/|title=Check Out: Marissa Nadler \u2013 \u201cThe Wrecking Ball Company\u201d|date=14 February 2012|publisher=|accessdate=1 October 2016}}</ref> Nadler announced the album on her Facebook page as a \"sister album\" to her 2011 [[Marissa Nadler (album)|eponymous]] album. The album was dubbed by ''[[Paste Magazine]]'' an \"impressive concoction of stark minimalism.\"<ref name=\"pastea\"/>\n\n==Track listing==\n# \"The Wrecking Ball Company\"\n# \"Love Again, There Is a Fire\"\n# \"Christine\"\n# \"Apostle\"\n# \"Constantine\"\n# \"To a Road, Love\"\n# \"In a Little Town\"\n# \"Your Heart Is a Twisted Vine\"\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.marissanadler.com/ Marissa Nadler Official Site]\n{{Marissa Nadler}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sister, The}}\n[[Category:2012 albums]]\n[[Category:Marissa Nadler albums]]\n\n\n{{2010s-folk-album-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Caro7200", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Sister"}
{"title_page": "Saumyendranath Tagore", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox Indian politician\n| honorific prefix = [[Comrade]]\n| name = Saumyendranath Tagore\n| image = Saumyendranath Tagore.jpg\n| caption = \n| birth_date= {{birth date|df=yes|1901|10|08}}\n| birth_place = [[Kolkata|Calcutta]], [[British India]]\n| alma_mater = [[Presidency University, Kolkata]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1974|09|22|1901|10|08}}\n| death_place =\n| occupation = [[Politician]], [[Marxism|Marxist theorist]]\n| party = [[Workers and Peasants Party]],<br> [[Communist Party of India]],<br> [[Communist Party of Germany]],<br> [[Revolutionary Communist Party of India]], <br> [[Revolutionary Communist Party of India (Tagore)]]\n| spouse = Srimati Hutheesing\n| children = \n| website ={{url|http://www.rcpicommunist.in/p/saumyendranath-tagore.html}}\n| footnotes = \n| date = \n| year = \n| source = \n|}}\n'''Saumyendranath Tagore''' (October 08, 1901&ndash;September 22, 1974)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ajms.co.in/sites/ajms2015/index.php/ajms/article/view/1764|title=Saumyendranath Tagore and the Peasant Movement of Murshidabad: A Study on Historical Perspectives|author=Bhattacharya, Satya Brata|date=April 2016}}</ref> , son of Sudhindranath Tagore , grandson of [[Dwijendranath Tagore]], and grand-nephew of [[Rabindranath Tagore]], was the leader of the [[Revolutionary Communist Party of India]],<ref>[[Dwijendranath Tagore#Descendants]]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Tagore,_Soumyendranath|title=Tagore, Soumyendranath - Banglapedia|website=en.banglapedia.org|language=en|access-date=2017-08-23}}</ref> and the first translator of [[The Communist Manifesto]] into [[Bengali_language|Bengali]], which was published in ''Langal'' magazine edited by Kaji Najrul.\n\n== Education ==\nTagore passed matriculation in 1917 from Mitra Institution in [[Kolkata]] and became graduate with Hon's in Economics from the [[Presidency University, Kolkata|Presidency University]] in the year of 1921.\n\n== Communist movement ==\nIn 1920, he joined the \"''[[Nikhil Bharat Chatra Sammelan]]''\" (\"All-India Student Conference\") in [[Ahmedabad]]. He befriended [[Muzaffar Ahmed (politician)|Muzaffar Ahmed]] and the poet, [[Kazi Nazrul Islam]]. \n\nAfter Tagore joined the Workers' and Peasants' Party (WPP) in April 1926, he began mobilizing the jute mill\u2010workers of Bengal to form the Bengal Jute Workers' Association. His effectiveness as a trade union activist and his attempts to win revolutionaries over to the WPP drew official attention to him. In order to avoid arrest, Tagore left for Europe in May 1927.<ref name=\"gupta\">{{cite web|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/9781405198073.wbierp1431|title=Tagore, Saumyendranath (1901\u20131974)|author=Shatarupa Sen Gupta|date=20 April 2009|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> There, he met international communist leaders and was soon in [[Moscow]]. He attended the 6th Congress of the [[Coummunist International]] ([[Comintern]]). \n\nTagore differed with the Comintern on the \u2033Colonial Question\u2033<ref name=\"gupta\"></ref>. Later, he came to favor [[Leon Trotsky]]'s theory of \"[[Permanent_revolution|Permanent Revolution]]\" over [[Joseph Stalin]]'s notion of \"[[Socialism in one country|Socialism in One Country]]\".<ref name=\"rcpi\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rcpi-communist.in/2018/09/on-44th-death-anniversary-of-comrade-sn.html|title=On the 44th death anniversary of Comrade S.N. Tagore|author=Revolutionary Communist Party of India|date=22 September 2018|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> He also came to oppose the Comintern's \"[[Popular_front#Comintern_policy:_1934\u20131939|Popular Front]]\" strategy in the 1930s, regarding as a betrayal of proletarian revolution.<ref name=\"rcpi\"></ref>\n\nDue to the continuous extremist works, British and German government imprisoned him. After returning in India, he was arrested again and imprisoned for almost eight years.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1934, Tagore formed the [[Revolutionary Communist Party of India]] (RCPI). But the party was divided afterwards.<ref name=\":0\">Sengupta, Subodh Chandra and Bose, Anjali (editors), ''Sansad Bangali Charitabhidhan'' (Biographical dictionary) Vol I, 1976/1998, {{in lang|bn}}, p. 607, {{ISBN|81-85626-65-0}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c71PAQAAIAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Society and Change|last=Volume 10|first=Mihir Purkayastha for the ASSC|date=1995|access-date=March 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Literary works ==\nSaumymendranath Tagore was a regular writer of ''Kallol'' group. He wrote articles in French, Russian, German, English and Bengali languages. The books ''Biplabi Russia, Trayee, Jatri, Rabindranather Gaan'', 'Communism and Fetishism', 'Bourgeois Democratic Revolution and India', 'Permanent Revolution', 'Tactics and strategy of revolution' 'Gandhi'(French) are few of them.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Family ==\nSaumyendranath Tagore married Srimati Hutheesingh from an aristocratic Jain Gujarati [[Hutheesing family]] of Ahmedabad. She was a student in Shantiniketan and a well known dancer and choreographer who took training in dance in India and abroad. Srimati Tagore's brother Gunottam (Raja) Hutheesingh married [[Krishna Nehru]], younger daughter of [[Motilal Nehru]] and sister of [[India]]'s first [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Jawaharlal Nehru]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Tagore family}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tagore, Soumendranath}}\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:1975 deaths]]\n[[Category:Tagore family|Soumendranath]]\n[[Category:Indian revolutionaries]]\n[[Category:Indian communists]]\n[[Category:Indian Marxists]]\n[[Category:Indian prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of British India]]\n[[Category:Indian political party founders]]\n[[Category:Revolutionary Communist Party of India politicians]]\n\n\n{{India-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox Indian politician\n| honorific prefix = [[Comrade]]\n| name = Saumyendranath Tagore\n| image = Saumyendranath Tagore.jpg\n| caption = \n| birth_date= {{birth date|df=yes|1901|10|08}}\n| birth_place = [[Kolkata|Calcutta]], [[British India]]\n| alma_mater = [[Presidency University, Kolkata]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1974|09|22|1901|10|08}}\n| death_place =\n| occupation = [[Politician]], [[Marxism|Marxist theorist]]\n| party = [[Workers and Peasants Party]],<br> [[Communist Party of India]],<br> [[Communist Party of Germany]],<br> [[Revolutionary Communist Party of India]], <br> [[Revolutionary Communist Party of India (Tagore)]]\n| spouse = Srimati Hutheesing\n| children = \n| website ={{url|http://www.rcpicommunist.in/p/saumyendranath-tagore.html}}\n| footnotes = \n| date = \n| year = \n| source = \n|}}\n'''Saumyendranath Tagore''' (October 08, 1901&ndash;September 22, 1974)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ajms.co.in/sites/ajms2015/index.php/ajms/article/view/1764|title=Saumyendranath Tagore and the Peasant Movement of Murshidabad: A Study on Historical Perspectives|author=Bhattacharya, Satya Brata|date=April 2016}}</ref> , son of Sudhindranath Tagore , grandson of [[Dwijendranath Tagore]], and grand-nephew of [[Rabindranath Tagore]], was the leader of the [[Revolutionary Communist Party of India]],<ref>[[Dwijendranath Tagore#Descendants]]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://en.banglapedia.org/index.php?title=Tagore,_Soumyendranath|title=Tagore, Soumyendranath - Banglapedia|website=en.banglapedia.org|language=en|access-date=2017-08-23}}</ref> and the first translator of [[The Communist Manifesto]] into [[Bengali_language|Bengali], which was published in ''Langal'' magazine edited by Kaji Najrul.\n\n== Education ==\nTagore passed matriculation in 1917 from Mitra Institution in [[Kolkata]] and became graduate with Hon's in Economics from the [[Presidency University, Kolkata|Presidency University]] in the year of 1921.\n\n== Communist movement ==\nIn 1920, he joined the \"''[[Nikhil Bharat Chatra Sammelan]]''\" (\"All-India Student Conference\") in [[Ahmedabad]]. He befriended [[Muzaffar Ahmed (politician)|Muzaffar Ahmed]] and the poet, [[Kazi Nazrul Islam]]. \n\nAfter Tagore joined the Workers' and Peasants' Party (WPP) in April 1926, he began mobilizing the jute mill\u2010workers of Bengal to form the Bengal Jute Workers' Association. His effectiveness as a trade union activist and his attempts to win revolutionaries over to the WPP drew official attention to him. In order to avoid arrest, Tagore left for Europe in May 1927.<ref name=\"gupta\">{{cite web|url=https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/abs/10.1002/9781405198073.wbierp1431|title=Tagore, Saumyendranath (1901\u20131974)|author=Shatarupa Sen Gupta|date=20 April 2009|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> There, he met international communist leaders and was soon in [[Moscow]]. He attended the 6th Congress of the [[Coummunist International]] ([[Comintern]]). \n\nTagore differed with the Comintern on the \u2033Colonial Question\u2033<ref name=\"gupta\"></ref>. Later, he came to favor [[Leon Trotsky]]'s theory of \"[[Permanent_revolution|Permanent Revolution]]\" over [[Joseph Stalin]]'s notion of \"[[Socialism in one country|Socialism in One Country]]\".<ref name=\"rcpi\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rcpi-communist.in/2018/09/on-44th-death-anniversary-of-comrade-sn.html|title=On the 44th death anniversary of Comrade S.N. Tagore|author=Revolutionary Communist Party of India|date=22 September 2018|access-date=13 April 2020}}</ref> He also came to oppose the Comintern's \"[[Popular_front#Comintern_policy:_1934\u20131939|Popular Front]]\" strategy in the 1930s, regarding as a betrayal of proletarian revolution.<ref name=\"rcpi\"></ref>\n\nDue to the continuous extremist works, British and German government imprisoned him. After returning in India, he was arrested again and imprisoned for almost eight years.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 1934, Tagore formed the [[Revolutionary Communist Party of India]] (RCPI). But the party was divided afterwards.<ref name=\":0\">Sengupta, Subodh Chandra and Bose, Anjali (editors), ''Sansad Bangali Charitabhidhan'' (Biographical dictionary) Vol I, 1976/1998, {{in lang|bn}}, p. 607, {{ISBN|81-85626-65-0}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=c71PAQAAIAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Society and Change|last=Volume 10|first=Mihir Purkayastha for the ASSC|date=1995|access-date=March 10, 2017}}</ref>\n\n== Literary works ==\nSaumymendranath Tagore was a regular writer of ''Kallol'' group. He wrote articles in French, Russian, German, English and Bengali languages. The books ''Biplabi Russia, Trayee, Jatri, Rabindranather Gaan'', 'Communism and Fetishism', 'Bourgeois Democratic Revolution and India', 'Permanent Revolution', 'Tactics and strategy of revolution' 'Gandhi'(French) are few of them.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Family ==\nSaumyendranath Tagore married Srimati Hutheesingh from an aristocratic Jain Gujarati [[Hutheesing family]] of Ahmedabad. She was a student in Shantiniketan and a well known dancer and choreographer who took training in dance in India and abroad. Srimati Tagore's brother Gunottam (Raja) Hutheesingh married [[Krishna Nehru]], younger daughter of [[Motilal Nehru]] and sister of [[India]]'s first [[Prime Minister of India|Prime Minister]] [[Jawaharlal Nehru]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{Tagore family}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tagore, Soumendranath}}\n[[Category:1910 births]]\n[[Category:1975 deaths]]\n[[Category:Tagore family|Soumendranath]]\n[[Category:Indian revolutionaries]]\n[[Category:Indian communists]]\n[[Category:Indian Marxists]]\n[[Category:Indian prisoners and detainees]]\n[[Category:Prisoners and detainees of British India]]\n[[Category:Indian political party founders]]\n[[Category:Revolutionary Communist Party of India politicians]]\n\n\n{{India-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Homo Huamanguensis", "label": "safe", "comment": "", 